---
title: "Comments on 'Natural Resources: The Laws of Their Scarcity'"
year: 1982
abstract: >
  Jaynes critiques the thermodynamic arguments presented by Nicholas
  Georgescu-Roegen (NGR) in his work on the economic implications of the Second
  Law of Thermodynamics. He argues that NGR's technical analysis is flawed due
  to a fundamental misunderstanding of the distinction between thermodynamic
  and mechanical reversibility, and that his "entropic predicament" is
  illusory. Jaynes provides a more optimistic outlook on long-range resource
  availability, energy, and food production, emphasizing the role of
  technological advancement and the earth's natural entropy-flushing
  mechanism through radiation into the night sky.
author: ["E.T. Jaynes"]
categories: ["Foundations of Probability & Bayesian Inference"]
tags: ["entropy", "reversibility", "second law of thermodynamics", "economics", "natural resources", "Gibbs", "Planck", "resource scarcity"]
---
